  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most common questions vendors ask before signing with an agent is: what does this actually cost me? The answer depends on what you negotiate, because Queensland does not regulate real estate commission rates. Unlike some other states, there is no official scale or cap. Every commission is a commercial negotiation between you and the agent, and what you agree to is what you pay.</p>

      <p>Understanding how commission works before you sit down with an agent puts you in a far stronger position to negotiate sensibly, and to avoid signing a Form 6 that disadvantages you. This article covers the standard structure, what is typical in Brisbane's inner east in 2027, and the details that catch sellers off guard.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The basic structure: commission is paid at settlement</h2>
      <p>Commission is calculated as a percentage of the final sale price and paid at settlement from the sale proceeds. You do not pay the agent upfront. The conveyancer or solicitor managing your settlement will deduct the commission (and any other agreed costs) from the purchase funds before transferring the balance to you. This means you never write the agent a cheque directly. It comes out of what you receive on settlement day.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east in 2027, typical residential commission rates for a standard campaign sit in the range of roughly 2% to 2.5% plus GST. On a $1.2 million sale at 2.2% plus GST, the commission is approximately $26,400 including GST. That is a meaningful cost and worth understanding precisely before you agree to anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Commission and VPA are not the same thing</h2>
      <p>Many sellers conflate two separate costs: the agent's commission and the vendor-paid advertising (VPA). They are distinct. Commission is what you pay the agent for selling the property. VPA is a separate cost to fund the marketing campaign: online listings, photography, social media, signage, and in some cases editorial or magazine placements.</p>

      <p>VPA is typically charged separately from commission, either as a fixed sum agreed before the campaign begins or as a capped amount within the Form 6. It is usually paid whether or not the property sells, though some agents will negotiate to waive or rebate VPA costs if the property fails to sell. Clarify this before signing. The total cost of selling is commission plus VPA plus any other fees (conveyancing, rates adjustments), so make sure you are working from the full number.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tiered commission structures and why they exist</h2>
      <p>Some agents offer a tiered or stepped commission structure: a lower base rate up to an agreed target price, and a higher rate on any amount above that target. For example, 2% on the first $1.1 million and 10% on anything above $1.1 million. The idea is straightforward: the agent has a direct financial incentive to push the sale price beyond the baseline, because they earn significantly more per dollar on the premium above the agreed target.</p>

      <p>Done properly, tiered structures align the agent's financial interest with yours. The risk is that the target price is set too conservatively, allowing the agent to earn the higher tier rate on results that were already achievable without exceptional effort. If you are considering a tiered structure, make sure the base tier price reflects a realistic but genuinely achievable outcome in the current market, not a deliberately low figure that inflates the agent's premium earnings.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When commission is owed: the Form 6 and effective cause</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, the agency agreement is formalised through a Form 6. This document sets out the commission rate, the authority period (how long the agent has exclusive rights to sell the property), and the trigger for commission to be payable. The standard trigger is "unconditional exchange" or "effective cause of sale." Read this carefully, because it determines when the agent earns their fee.</p>

      <p>The effective cause principle is the one that catches sellers off guard most often. If a buyer inspects your property during the agency period and later purchases the property after the authority period has expired, some agents will still claim commission on the basis that they were the effective cause of the sale. Whether this claim has merit depends on the specific circumstances and the wording of the Form 6. The practical implication: keep records of who inspected during the agency period, and if you are selling privately after an agency period ends, get legal advice before proceeding if any of those buyers re-enter the picture.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Rebates and referral fees the agent must disclose</h2>
      <p>Agents in Queensland have a legal obligation to disclose any financial benefit they receive from third parties in connection with your sale. This includes referral fees from conveyancers, financial planners, mortgage brokers, or insurers they recommend to buyers or to you. If your agent recommends a conveyancer and receives a referral fee for doing so, that must be disclosed in writing before you engage the referred service.</p>

      <p>This is not uncommon in the industry, and it does not necessarily mean the referral is a bad one. But you should know about it, and you should feel free to use your own conveyancer regardless of who the agent recommends.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should and should not negotiate</h2>
      <p>There are four things worth raising when negotiating your commission arrangement: the rate itself, the VPA cap, the authority period, and whether a tiered structure makes sense for your property. Most sellers focus exclusively on the rate and miss the other three.</p>

      <p>The authority period is particularly important. An exclusive authority of 90 days is standard, but 60 days is reasonable for a well-priced property in an active market. A shorter authority period keeps the agent accountable and gives you the option to change direction more quickly if the campaign is not performing.</p>

      <p>What sellers should not do is negotiate every element simultaneously to the point of demotivating the agent. An agent who feels the fee is not worth the effort will not bring the same energy to your campaign as one who feels properly compensated. The goal is a fair arrangement that gives the agent genuine incentive to achieve a strong result, not the lowest possible fee regardless of consequences.</p>

